{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014N9aCuYFaWZX8PPFfNevfj","type":"tool_result","content":"| D004 | Build Kalshi Arbitrage Engine (Wen Zhou) | **PHASE 1: Market Filtering (Daily Scan).** Filter Kalshi markets by: (1) Volume ≥10,000 (exclude low-liquidity noise), (2) YES/NO ratio targets: 15-30% or 70-85% (mispriced range). Reject middle 40-60% (too efficient, no edge). Reject extremes 0-15% & 85-100% (distorted pricing). Rationale: Extreme ratios have unrealistic implied probabilities; middle range reflects consensus (no inefficiency). Output: filtered market list for Phase 2. **PHASE 2: LLM-Based Clustering (Daily Scan).** Use LLM embeddings to identify hidden market correlations. Group similar markets (e.g., Bitcoin $100k + Ethereum $5k + Crypto dominance all cluster together). Find markets with strong semantic/causal links that traditional screening misses. Output: market clusters for Phase 3. **PHASE 3: Pearson Pairwise Correlation Detection (Daily Scan).** Apply Pearson/distance-based algorithm (ref: hudson-and-thames-arbitragelab) to detect strongly correlated market pairs. Identify mispricings: if BTC moves +5% in backtest but only +2% in live, that's arbitrage. Calculate expected spread from historical correlation. Score confidence. Output: correlation_pairs.json with arbitrage candidates. **PHASE 4: C++ High-Frequency Execution (Real-Time).** Why C++: Each trade moves prices; we need sub-millisecond execution to capture arbitrage before it reverts. Algorithm: (1) Detect spread gap between correlated markets, (2) Calculate theoretical fair spread, (3) Execute buy/sell pairs to lock profit, (4) Monitor until convergence. No Python delays. No GIL. Pure performance. **Why This Works:** Phases 1-3 reduce noise (99% of markets ignored), find real edges via correlation-based pairs (harder to game than single-market signals), Phase 4 captures spread before reversion. This is the real edge. Reference: https://hudson-and-thames-arbitragelab.readthedocs-hosted.com/en/latest/distance_approach/pearson_approach.html | high | all | undefined | open | 2026-04-03 | 2026-04-03 | Wen Zhou strategy — full 4-phase pipeline. Phases 1-3 = daily batch. Phase 4 = real-time. Blocks live trading pending T236 (API credentials). |\n| 429 | Fix GET /api/tasks/:id returning 404 (missing route) | E2E test `ui_verify.spec.js` test #19 confirms a bug: GET /api/tasks/:id returns 404 because the route is not implemented in `server.js` or `backend/api.js`.  The API supports: - PATCH /api/tasks/:id - DELETE /api/tasks/:id - POST /api/tasks/:id/claim - GET /api/tasks/:id/result  But GET /api/tasks/:id (fetch single task) is missing.  Deliverable: 1. Add `GET /api/tasks/:id` route that returns the task object (same format as list items) 2. Run the E2E test to verify the bug is fixed 3. Update any related tests if needed | medium | all | dave | in_progress | 2026-04-03 | 2026-04-03 |  |\n| 431 | Fix GET /api/tasks/:id returning 404 | E2E test ui_verify.spec.js test #19 confirms a bug: GET /api/tasks/:id returns 404 because the route is not implemented in server.js or backend/api.js.  The API supports PATCH, DELETE, POST /api/tasks/:id/claim, and GET /api/tasks/:id/result — but GET /api/tasks/:id (fetch single task) is missing.  Deliverable: 1. Add GET /api/tasks/:id route that returns the task object 2. Run E2E test to verify bug is fixed 3. Update any related tests if needed | medium | all | dave | open | 2026-04-03 | 2026-04-03 |  |","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cdc38eb2-8e84-4ba4-a86a-56104d2ecaf3","uuid":"8dd3b1f2-5d6b-410a-aaab-04612b1ba730","timestamp":"2026-04-03T23:24:52.829Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"| D004 | Build Kalshi Arbitrage Engine (Wen Zhou) | **PHASE 1: Market Filtering (Daily Scan).** Filter Kalshi markets by: (1) Volume ≥10,000 (exclude low-liquidity noise), (2) YES/NO ratio targets: 15-30% or 70-85% (mispriced range). Reject middle 40-60% (too efficient, no edge). Reject extremes 0-15% & 85-100% (distorted pricing). Rationale: Extreme ratios have unrealistic implied probabilities; middle range reflects consensus (no inefficiency). Output: filtered market list for Phase 2. **PHASE 2: LLM-Based Clustering (Daily Scan).** Use LLM embeddings to identify hidden market correlations. Group similar markets (e.g., Bitcoin $100k + Ethereum $5k + Crypto dominance all cluster together). Find markets with strong semantic/causal links that traditional screening misses. Output: market clusters for Phase 3. **PHASE 3: Pearson Pairwise Correlation Detection (Daily Scan).** Apply Pearson/distance-based algorithm (ref: hudson-and-thames-arbitragelab) to detect strongly correlated market pairs. Identify mispricings: if BTC moves +5% in backtest but only +2% in live, that's arbitrage. Calculate expected spread from historical correlation. Score confidence. Output: correlation_pairs.json with arbitrage candidates. **PHASE 4: C++ High-Frequency Execution (Real-Time).** Why C++: Each trade moves prices; we need sub-millisecond execution to capture arbitrage before it reverts. Algorithm: (1) Detect spread gap between correlated markets, (2) Calculate theoretical fair spread, (3) Execute buy/sell pairs to lock profit, (4) Monitor until convergence. No Python delays. No GIL. Pure performance. **Why This Works:** Phases 1-3 reduce noise (99% of markets ignored), find real edges via correlation-based pairs (harder to game than single-market signals), Phase 4 captures spread before reversion. This is the real edge. Reference: https://hudson-and-thames-arbitragelab.readthedocs-hosted.com/en/latest/distance_approach/pearson_approach.html | high | all | undefined | open | 2026-04-03 | 2026-04-03 | Wen Zhou strategy — full 4-phase pipeline. Phases 1-3 = daily batch. Phase 4 = real-time. Blocks live trading pending T236 (API credentials). |\n| 429 | Fix GET /api/tasks/:id returning 404 (missing route) | E2E test `ui_verify.spec.js` test #19 confirms a bug: GET /api/tasks/:id returns 404 because the route is not implemented in `server.js` or `backend/api.js`.  The API supports: - PATCH /api/tasks/:id - DELETE /api/tasks/:id - POST /api/tasks/:id/claim - GET /api/tasks/:id/result  But GET /api/tasks/:id (fetch single task) is missing.  Deliverable: 1. Add `GET /api/tasks/:id` route that returns the task object (same format as list items) 2. Run the E2E test to verify the bug is fixed 3. Update any related tests if needed | medium | all | dave | in_progress | 2026-04-03 | 2026-04-03 |  |\n| 431 | Fix GET /api/tasks/:id returning 404 | E2E test ui_verify.spec.js test #19 confirms a bug: GET /api/tasks/:id returns 404 because the route is not implemented in server.js or backend/api.js.  The API supports PATCH, DELETE, POST /api/tasks/:id/claim, and GET /api/tasks/:id/result — but GET /api/tasks/:id (fetch single task) is missing.  Deliverable: 1. Add GET /api/tasks/:id route that returns the task object 2. Run E2E test to verify bug is fixed 3. Update any related tests if needed | medium | all | dave | open | 2026-04-03 | 2026-04-03 |  |","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
